header.description: Tang2020 - Estimation of transmission risk of COVID-19 and impact of public health interventions

ModelDetails.model_description: The model is a deterministic compartmental model called 'Susceptible-Exposed-Infectious-Recovered' (SEIR), which is based on the clinical progression of the disease, epidemiological status of individuals, and intervention measures. It likely can be represented in petrinet format due to its compartmental nature.
ModelDetails.FundedBy: National Natural Science Foundation of China, Canada Research Chair Program, and the Natural Sciences and Engineering Research Council of Canada.

Evaluation.TestingDataFactorsMetrics: The model was validated using Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods and likelihood-based estimation, with data obtained for confirmed cases of 2019-nCoV in mainland China.

Uses.OutOfScopeUse: Using the model for diseases with significantly different transmission characteristics or in populations with different social behaviors may be inappropriate.
Uses.DirectUse: The model can be used to predict the peak and spread of infectious diseases, specifically for the 2019-nCoV, and to analyze the effectiveness of interventions such as quarantine, isolation, and travel restrictions.

HowToGetStartedWithTheModel.examples: To use the model, one would need to input data such as the number of exposed individuals, contact rates, and quarantine rates. The model then simulates the spread of the virus and the effectiveness of public health interventions.

BiasRisksLimitations.bias_risks_limitations: The model's estimates are based on data collected during a period of intensive social contacts, which may not be representative of other periods. The quality of data improves over time, and initial datasets may lack crucial information, affecting the accuracy of the model's predictions.

TechnicalSpecifications.model_specs: The model includes multiple compartments such as susceptible, exposed, infectious (symptomatic and asymptomatic), hospitalized, and recovered, along with quarantined states for each. It involves parameters like contact rate, transmission probability, quarantine rate, and recovery rate.

references: Tang, B., Wang, X., Li, Q., Bragazzi, N.L., Tang, S., Xiao, Y., & Wu, J. (2020). Estimation of the Transmission Risk of the 2019-nCoV and Its Implication for Public Health Interventions. Journal of Clinical Medicine, 9(2), 462.

SEIR_EstimationModel.model_summary: This model estimates the transmission risk of the 2019-nCoV and evaluates the impact of public health interventions.
